Database

  • Database is a structured collection of data
  • It may be anything from simple shopping list to picture gallery or information in a corporate network
  • Add, Access and process data stored in a computer database, you need a database management system such as MySQL Server
  • Since computers are very good at handling large amounts of data, database management systems play a central role in computing as standalone ulitiies or as part of other applications

Relational Database

  • Called Relational Database Management Systems (SQL Databases)
  • Structured Query Language or SQL is used to do set operations (Union, Intersect, Minus) to organize and retrieve information
based on set theory and relational algebra
  • In any system that uses SQL, Data elements or attributes categorized into columns are related into tuples (rows)
  • Sets of relations with identical structure form tables. These elements, correlated rows, columns and tables form the basis for a RDMS

Business Uses of SQL

  • Access and manipulate information
  • Generate reports to aid decision making process
  • Make it easier to import and export data to/from different systems
  • Facilitate finding and supporting roles using data analysis
  • Provide strict ACID constraints to data assets

Relational Databases

  • RDBMS are used in most large enterprises with the exception of MySQL also used to store data for Web applications.

  • Oracle
    • multi-model database management system
  • MySQL
    • Open-source RDBMS based on SQL. Runs on virtually all platforms.
  • Microsoft SQL Server
    • RDBMS supporting a wide variety of transaction processing, business intelligence, and analytics apps in corporate IT environments
  • PostgresSQL
    • Object-relational database management system (ORDBMS) with emphasis on extensibility and standards compliance
  • DB2
    • DB2 is an RDBMS designed to store, analyze and retrieve data efficiently

ACID Properties

  • Transaction is a logical unit of work which accesses and possibly modifies content of a database. Transactions access data via read and write operations.

  • In order to maintain consistency before and after a transaction certain properties are followed these are called ACID

  • Atomicity
    • Either entire transaction takes place at once or not at all (Abort or Commit)
  • Consistency
    • Means integrity constraints must be maintained to that the database is consistent before and after the transaction. Refers to the correctness of a database.
  • Isolation
    • This property ensures that multiple transactions can occur concurrently without leading to the inconsistency of database state.
  • Duarability
    • This property ensures that once the transaction has completed execution, the updates and modifications to the database are stored in and written to disk and they persist even if a system failure occurs.

Transition to Non-Relational Databases

Due to growth of data over the last 10 years and new data types non-relational databases have grown after decades of RDBMS

Non-Relational Databases

  • Also Called NoSQL databases
  • NoSQL are built on non-realtional technology
  • More accurate to define NoSQL  about how data is stored and not how to query
  • NoSQL is industry standard term but beginning to lose popularity as does not cover complexity and range on non-relational data stores available
  • Most Known are:
        • MongoDB
        • DocumentDB
        • Cassandra
        • Coachbase
        • HBase
        • Redis
        • Neo4J

NoSQL fall under four main categories:

  • Document
    • Stores a business subject in one structure called a document instead of breaking up into different tables
      • Single document called Registration would contain Student, Course, Registraion instead of 3 distinct relational structures
  • Key Value
    • Stores data in 2 columns Key and Value
      • Simple (dates, numbers, codes) and complex information(unformatted text, video, music, documents and photos) within the key and value column respectively
  • Coumn-Orientated
    • Looks as data as rows and columns like a RDBMS. However can handle more ambiguous and complex data types, unformatted text and imagery. In addition column-orientatd databases store each column in its own structure.
  • Graph
    • Represents data whose relations are well represented as a set of nodes with an undetermined number of connections between these nodes. Good candidates for a graph database include:
      • Social Relationships (nodes are people)
      • Public Transport Links (node can be bus or train stations)
      • Roadmaps (nodes street intersections or highway intersections)
      • Anything requiring traversing a graph to find the shortest routes, nearest neighbours etc)

Business uses of NoSQL

  • Deploy new, innovative applications, in addition to migrating infrastructure from on-premise to cloud
  • Create data models, evaluate alternatives, find problems early and to think through data processes
  • Satisfy the need for a very agile delivery system that is easily able to process unstructured and dynamic data
  • Prepare unstructured or messy data for analysis
  • Implement a scale out architecture for high performance data management needs.

Differences Between Relational + Non-Relational Databases

Finish on Wednesday


Relational Database Advantages

  • Relational databases work with structured data
  • Support ACID transactional consistency and support 'joins'
  • Built-in data integrity and a large eco-system
  • Relationships in this system have constraints
  • Limitless indexing. Strong SQL
  • Relational databases are well-documented and mature technologies, RDBMs are sold and maintained by established corporations
  • SQL standards are well-defined and commonly accepted
  • Large pool of qualified developers have experience with SQL and RDBMS
  • All RDBMS are ACID-compliant, meaning they satisfy the requirements of Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation and Durability

Disadvantages of RDBMs

  • Relational Databases do not scale out horizontally very well (concurrency and data size) only vertically (unless you are sharding)
  • Data is normalized meaning lots of joins which affects speed
  • They have problems working with semi-structured data
  • RDBMS dont work well or at all with unstructured or semi-structured data due to schema and type constraints. This makes them ill-suited for large analytics or IoT even loads.
  • The tables in you relational database will not neccessarily map one-to-one with an object or class representing the same data.
  • When migrating one RDBMS to another, schemas and types must be identical between source and destination tables for migration to work (schema constraint). For many of the same reasons, extremely complex datasets or those containing variable-length records are generally difficult to handle with an RDBMS schema.

NoSQL/Non-Relational Databases

  • NoSQL databases emerged as a popular alternative to relational databases as web applications became increasingly complex
  • NoSQL/non-relational databases can take a variety of forms
  • However, the critical difference between NoSQL and relational databases is that RDBMS schemas rigidly define how all data inserted into the database must be typed and composed, where as NoSQL databases can be schema-agnostic, allowing unstructured and semi-structured data to be stored and manipulated.

Advantages Non-relational/NoSQL

  • They scale out horizontally and work with unstructured and semi-structured data. Some support ACID transactional consistency.
  • Schema-free or Schema-on-read options
  • High availability
  • While many NoSQL databases are open source and so 'Free' there are often considerably training, setup and development costs. There are now also numerous commercial products available. 
  • Schema-free data models are more flexible and easier to administer
  • NoSQL databases are generally more horizontally scalable and fault-tolerant
  • Data can easily be distributed across different nodes. To improve availability and/or partition tolerance, you can choose that data on some nodes be eventually consistent

Disadvantages Non-Relational/NoSQL

  • Weaker or eventual consistency (BASE) instead of ACID
    • Basically Available Soft State Eventual Consistency
  • Limited support for joins
  • Data is denormalized, requireing mass updates (I.e. Product name change)
  • Does not have built-in data integrity (must do in code)
  • Limited indexing
  • NoSQL databases are generally less widely adopted and mature than RDBMS solutions, so specific expertise often required
  • There is a range of formats and constraints specific to each database

Uses for different Database Technologies

  • For traditional OLTP Business systems (i.e. ERP, CRM, In-House app) relational databases (RDBMS) are still the primary and most efficient choice.  Other choices are:
    • Data Warehouses (OLAP) are good for relational database (SMP or MPP)
    • Web and mobile global OLTP applications work well with non-relational database (NoSQL)
    • Data lakes are good for Hadoop
    • Relational and scalable OLTP would work well with NewSQL

When to Use NoSQL

  • When bringing in new data with a lot of volume and/or variety
  • Data is non-relational/semi-structured
  • Your team will be trained in these new technologies (NoSQL)
  • You have enough information to correctly select the type of and product of NoSQL for your situation
  • You can relax transactional consistency when scalability or performance is more important
  • You can service a large number of user requests vs rigorously enforcing business rules.

SQL/RDBMS/Relational Databases

  • Relational databases and related management systems (RDBMS) are more widely known and understood than their NoSQL cousins.
  • Relational databases emerged in the 70s to store data according to a schema that allows data to be displayed as tables with rows and columns
  • Think of a relational database as a collection of tables, each with a schema that represents the fixed attributes and data types that the items in the table will have
  • RDBMS all provide functionality for reading, creating, updating and deleting data, typically by means of Structured Query Language (SQL) statements
  • The tables in a relational database have keys associated with them which are used to identify specific columns or rows of a table and facilitate faster access to a particular table, row or column of interest
  • Data integrity is of particular concern in relational databases, and RDBMS use a number of contsraints to ensure that the data contained in your tables are reliable and accurate
  • While there are many relational databases, over time, these have become the most popular.

Choosing Right Database Type

  • For a long time, relational databases were the standard for data management and processing with many enterprises and smaller companies working with SQL enabled relational databases.
  • These databases are organized by table with each data type contained with specific tables.
  • Keys are used to tie data between the different tables in order to construct complete data models
  • With the growth of internet technologies, NoSQL databases regained popularity and appeared in a significant number of implementations

Which Database is Right for You

  • This post looks only at the most popular and best-known examples of thes types of databases. 
  • If ACID compliance is 1st priority consider using RDBMS
  • If massive distributed system and can settle for eventual consistency on some nodes/partitions, consider wide column store such as Cassandra or Scylla
  • If input data is particulary heterogeneous and difficult to encapsulate according to a normalization schema consider using a NoSQL BDMS
  • If goal is to scale vertically consider and RDBMS conversely if you want to scale horizontally a NoSQL DBMS may be preferable

Data Definition Operations

  • SQL commands are in four categories:
    • DDL (Data Definitiion Language)
    • DML (Data Manipulation Language)
    • DCL (Data Control Language)
    • TCL (Transaction Control Language)

DDL (Data Definition Language)

  • DDL consists of SQL commands that can be used to define the database schema. It is used to create and modify the structure of database objects in database.

  • Examples of DDL commands include:
    • Create
    • Drop
    • Alter

 

 

SQL Constraints

  • NOT NULL
    • Ensures that column does not accept nulls
  • UNIQUE
    • Ensures all values in column are unique
  • DEFAULT
    • Assigns value to attribute when a new row is added to table
  • CHECK
    • Validates data when attribute value 

SQL Keys
  • A Key in SQL is a value used to identify records in a table uniquely
  • An SQL KEY is a single column or combination of multiple columns used to uniquely identify rows or tuples in the table
  • SQL Key is used to identify duplicate information and it also helps establish a relationship between multiple tables in the database

SQL Keys: Primary Key
  • A primary is a single column value used to identify a database record uniquely
    • A Primary key cannot be NULL
    • A Primary Key value must be Unique
    • Primary key values should rarely be changed
    • Primary Key must be given a value when a new record is inserted.

SQL Keys: Compostite Keys

  • A composite key is a primary key composed of multiple columns used to identify a record uniquely

 


SQL Keys: Foriegn Key

  • A composite key is a primary key composed of multiple columns used to identify a record Foriegn Key references the primary key of another Table! It helps connect your tables

  • A  foriegn key can have a different name from its primary key
  • It ensures rows in one table have corresponding rows in another
  • Unlike the Primary Key, they do not have to be unique. Most often they aren't
  • Foriegn Keys can be null even though primary keys cannot be unique
 


Why do you need a Foriegn Key?

  • Supposes insert a record in Table B as:

 
You will only be able to insert values into your foriegn key that exsist in the the unique key in the parent table. This helps in referential integrity.

The above problem can be overcome by declaring memberbship id from Table2 as foriegn key of membership id from table1

Now if someone tries to insert a value in the memebership id field that does not exsist in the parent table, an error will be shown!

DDL (Data Manipulation Language)

DML consists of SQL commands that deal with the manipulation of data present in a database. This includes most of the SQL statements.

Examples of DML commands include:
  • SELECT
  • INSERT
  • UPDATE
  • DELETE

 


DCL (Data Control Language)

  • DCL includes commands such as GRANT and REVOKE, which mainly deal with the rights, permissoions and other controls of the database system.

  • Examples of DCL commands include:
    • GRANT
    • REVOKE

TCL (Transaction Control Language)

  • TCL commands deal with transactions withing the database (transactions group a set of tasks into a single execution unit)
  • Examples:
    • COMMIT - commits a transaction
    • ROLLBACK- rolls back a transaction if an error occurs
    • SAVEPOINT- Setes a savepoint within a transaction
